Within vertical strata in the habitat, body mass might be a strong factor determining non-random patterns of species association. Differently sized species may exploit resources that differ to such a degree that large species might be unable to facilitate the foraging of small species and vice versa. Similarly, differently sized species might have different predators and, for a given species, joining a flock with members that are much larger or smaller than itself might not provide the same anti-predator benefits that could accrue from joining flocks of similarly sized species. However, apart from body mass, species-specific factors such as sentinel behaviour and efficiency in flushing prey, as well as structural characteristics of the habitat might also play a role in influencing species associations (
Kotagama and Goodale 2004
; 
Sridhar et al. 2009
).

Flocking species were dominated by insectivores, but included omnivores and nectarivores that also feed on insects and arthropods. Granivores, frugivores and carnivores never participated in flocks, reinforcing the observation that mixed-species flocks are composed mainly of insectivorous bird species (
Moynihan 1962
). Compared with resources such as fruit, which are likely to be localized, insects and arthropods are expected to be more evenly distributed in the habitat. Hence, insectivorous species might need to flock to facilitate foraging on a resource that is not localized or readily accessible. Such foraging benefits might arise from multiple independent mechanisms such as social learning about resource locations, increased foraging rates from prey flushing, and increased time available for foraging from decreased predation risk in a flock (
Krebs 1973
; review in 
Sridhar et al. 2009
). Provisioning experiments or natural outbreaks that might significantly increase local densities of arthropod or insect prey would serve as a useful test of the hypothesis that the distribution of prey affects flocking behaviour (see 
Hobson and van Wilgenburg 2006
).

Different foraging groups, because of their specialized behaviours, are likely to contribute qualitatively and quantitatively different benefits to heterospecifics in mixedspecies flocks. For instance, gregarious foliage gleaners are likely to flush insects or other active prey, making these accessible to salliers (
Swynnerton 1915
), and salliers, because they scan for insect prey, are likely to detect predators and provide early warning (
Munn 1984
; 
Goodale and Kotagama 2005
). These specialized functional contributions might have the consequence of balancing foraging method representation in the “core” of a mixed-species flock. In other words, core species composition of a mixed-species flock is likely to be heterogeneous and stable as a result of the exchange of specialized, and possibly complementary benefits between individuals in the core of the flock.
